[
<collectingRegion box="[370,478,1499,1523]" country="Russia" name="Volgograd" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Volgograd</collectingRegion>
] (MNHN).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,1569,2028]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
This and the following two species make up a distinct group of large, characteristic, halophilic species with distinct sexual dimorphism. Morphologically, the group is separated from other members of the genus by the distally coincident forewing veins 
<specimenCode box="[402,435,1641,1667]" collectionCode="R" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">R1</specimenCode>
and 
<specimenCode box="[490,526,1641,1667]" collectionCode="R" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">R2</specimenCode>
. The larvae of all three species feed in the roots of large, broad-leaved species of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,265,1678,1703]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plumbaginaceae" genus="Limonium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,1678,1703]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Limonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Bartel, M." box="[488,638,1677,1703]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="51 - 52" refId="ref55834" refString="Bartel, M. (1912) 24. Familie: Aegeriidae (Sesiidae). In: Seitz, Die Grossschmetterlinge der Erde. Vol. 2. A. Kernen, Stuttgart, pp. 375 - 416, pls. 51 - 52." type="book chapter" year="1912">Bartel (1912)</bibRefCitation>
is based on 
<specimenCount box="[774,900,1677,1704]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="female">one female</specimenCount>
, which is clearly the 
<typeStatus box="[1134,1236,1677,1703]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">holotype</typeStatus>
: “[...] fand ich bei Uralsk ein sehr gut erhaltenes 
<specimenCount box="[490,511,1714,1740]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
[...]. Von Uralsk (
<date box="[713,854,1713,1739]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" value="1907-07-04">
<collectingDate box="[713,854,1713,1739]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" value="1907-07-04">4. July 1907</collectingDate>
</date>
), Type in meiner Sammlung”. 
<collectorName box="[1195,1239,1713,1739]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">The</collectorName>
second specimen is mentioned subsequently “Bei einem 
<specimenCount box="[585,606,1750,1776]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
von Sarepta [...]”, and is therefore a 
<typeStatus box="[1013,1113,1750,1776]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">paratype</typeStatus>
. 
<collectorName box="[1122,1166,1749,1775]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">The</collectorName>
specimens were erroneously designated as 
<typeStatus box="[376,479,1785,1811]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">lectotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[533,684,1785,1811]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">paralectotype</typeStatus>
by 
<collectorName box="[726,829,1787,1814]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Špatenka</collectorName>
&amp; 
<collectorName box="[864,967,1785,1812]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Laštůvka</collectorName>
(1988).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,1569,2028]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1821,1847]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Barcodes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bartel" authorityYear="1912" box="[323,428,1822,1847]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Chamaesphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cirgisa">
<emphasis box="[323,428,1822,1847]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">P. cirgisa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the following two species form a distinct clade, which is also well-supported by morphological and biological evidence as outlined above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="51" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,1569,2028]" lastBlockId="51.[151,1437,151,717]" lastPageId="51" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,446,1893,1919]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Biology and habitat.</emphasis>
This species occurs in salt steppes with stands of large 
<taxonomicName box="[1095,1307,1893,1919]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plumbaginaceae" genus="Limonium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1095,1209,1894,1919]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Limonium</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
The larvae feed in the upper part of the root. Development takes one year. In Central 
<collectingCountry box="[971,1067,1929,1955]" name="Turkey" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
we found adult larvae and pupae in a large, perennial 
<taxonomicName box="[384,498,1966,1991]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plumbaginaceae" genus="Limonium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[384,498,1966,1991]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Limonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that dries up after flowering. Only plants that had an inflorescence from the previous year were infested. The flight period is in June and July. 
<bibRefCitation author="Zukowsky, B." box="[835,1035,2001,2028]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" pagination="77 - 79" refId="ref61947" refString="Zukowsky, B. (1915) Aphoristische Skizze uber die bisher bekannt gewordenen Futterpflanzen der palaarktischen Aegeriidae. Internationale Entomologische Zeitschrift, Guben, 9, 77 - 79." type="journal article" year="1915">Zukowsky (1915)</bibRefCitation>
states 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuntze" authorityName="Kuntze" authorityYear="1891" baseAuthorityName="Willd." box="[1113,1406,2001,2028]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plumbaginaceae" genus="Limonium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gmelini">
<emphasis box="[1113,1317,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Limonium gmelini</emphasis>
Kuntze
</taxonomicName>
as hostplant of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bartel" authorityYear="1912" box="[294,400,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Chamaesphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cirgisa">
<emphasis box="[294,400,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">P. cirgisa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[646,760,151,176]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plumbaginaceae" genus="Limonium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[646,760,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Limonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
constitute the hostplants of this species in Central 
<collectingCountry box="[1340,1436,151,177]" name="Turkey" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[159,243,187,214]" name="Turkey" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Turkey</collectingCountry>
) (pers. observation Lingenhöle, Bartsch). The habitats of this species, salt steppes and lakes, are critically endangered by grazing or drainage and conversion into arable land. Therefore, this species is of considerable conservation value.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,294,320]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Distribution.</emphasis>
Very local in south-eastern Europe (south-western 
<collectingCountry box="[920,997,295,321]" name="Russia" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1008,1100,295,322]" name="Ukraine" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
) and south-western Asia (
<collectingCountry name="Turkey" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, western Kazachstan) (
<bibRefCitation author="Lastuvka, Z. &amp; Lastuvka, A." box="[454,765,330,357]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref58916" refString="Lastuvka, Z. &amp; Lastuvka, A. (1995) An Illustrated Key to European Sesiidae (Lepidoptera). Faculty of Agronomy, Mendel University of Agriculture and Forestry, Brno, 174 pp." type="book" year="1995">Laštůvka &amp; Laštůvka 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lastuvka, Z. &amp; Lastuvka, A." box="[777,836,331,357]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref58954" refString="Lastuvka, Z. &amp; Lastuvka, A. (2001) The Sesiidae of Europe. Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 245 pp." type="book" year="2001">2001</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Spatenka, K. &amp; Gorbunov, O. &amp; Lastuvka, Z. &amp; Tosevski, I. &amp; Arita, Y." box="[848,1083,331,359]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" refId="ref61296" refString="Spatenka, K., Gorbunov, O., Lastuvka, Z., Tosevski, I. &amp; Arita, Y. (1999) s. n. In: Naumann, C. (Ed.), Handbook of Palaearctic Macrolepidoptera. Vol. 1. Sesiidae - Clearwing Moths. Gem Publishing Company, Wallingford, pp. 1 - 569." type="book" year="1999">
Špatenka 
<emphasis box="[959,1016,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">et al.</emphasis>
1999
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Garrevoet, T. &amp; Garrevoet, W. &amp; Ozbek, H." box="[1095,1341,331,357]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" pagination="929 - 953" refId="ref56949" refString="Garrevoet, T., Garrevoet, W. &amp; Ozbek, H. (2007) Data of the Geographic Distribution of Sesiidae (Lepidoptera) in Turkey. Linzer biologische Beitrage, 39 (2), 929 - 953." type="journal article" year="2007">
Garrevoet 
<emphasis box="[1215,1272,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
). An old record from 
<collectingCountry box="[291,392,367,393]" name="Romania" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Romania</collectingCountry>
is questionable. 
